    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During high-intensity exercise, your muscles switch to anaerobic glycolysis to generate energy quickly, producing lactate along with pyruvate when oxygen supply cannot keep up with demand. The burning sensation you feel is primarily caused by accumulated hydrogen ions from acid-base imbalances, not the lactate itself. Your body efficiently clears lactate back up into the bloodstream and liver within minutes to hours, where it is used as fuel or converted back into glucose via the Cori cycle.",
