    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but can you go into a bit more detail about the \"disruption\" part? Like, when those hydrogen ions and lactate start piling up, what is actually happening at the cellular level to cause that fatigue and \"burn\" feeling? It almost sounds like something is interfering with the normal muscle function.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly! While the specific trigger for the burning sensation is now known to be hydrogen ion accumulation affecting protein conformation—hyperlactatemia (high lactate) often accompanies this but isn't the culprit—the intense work causes rapid ATP consumption. When ATP shortage forces contract proteins into an unstable conformation, it leads to the fatigue and weakness you feel. Additionally, high levels of lactate act as an obligate oligomerizer, meaning it physically clusters with other proteins to alter their structure, further reducing muscle power output.",
      "source": "target",
